---
import GeneExplorer from '../components/GeneExplorer'
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'
---

<Base
  title="Gene explorer — JBrowseMSA"
  description="Type any human gene and get a connected JBrowse session: a collapsed-intron gene view, its 100-way protein alignment, and the AlphaFold structure — synthesized in the browser from a parsed GFF."
  wide
>
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>Gene explorer</h1>
    <p>
      Type any human gene. This page resolves it to its canonical (MANE / RefSeq
      Select) transcript, <strong>parses the GFF in your browser</strong>, and
      synthesizes a <strong>connected JBrowse session</strong> on the fly:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        a <strong>collapsed-intron</strong> Linear Genome View — the introns are
        squeezed out so the whole coding model fits at codon resolution,
      </li>
      <li>
        the gene's <strong>100-way vertebrate protein alignment</strong> beside
        it (react-msaview), connected so residues and codons share coordinates,
      </li>
      <li>
        and the <strong>AlphaFold structure</strong>, connected to the same
        genome view.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      There is no <code>collapseIntrons</code> option in JBrowse — the trick is
      to give the Linear Genome View a <code>loc</code> made of the exon ranges,
      space-separated. Each becomes one displayed region, rendered back-to-back,
      so the introns disappear. Everything below is computed live from public
      data (mygene.info, the UCSC RefSeq Select GFF over tabix, AlphaFold); only
      the alignment slice comes from a hosted file.
    </p>

    <GeneExplorer client:only="react" />
  </article>
</Base>
